Mycelium is not a workflow tool. It is not a spec tracker. It is
not a linter or a CI check. It is a connective layer.

Git tracks WHAT changed. Mycelium tracks WHY, and what it means,
and what to watch out for, and what we believe. Git is the skeleton.
Mycelium is the nervous system.

It is organic: notes grow naturally as agents work. No schema
migration, no required fields beyond kind, no closed vocabulary.
A note written today with 'kind celebration' works without any
change to the tool.

It is deterministic: git notes are content-addressed blobs on a
ref. They have commit history. They merge. They push and pull.
There is no magic, no database, no daemon. Just git.

It is minimal: two files (mycelium.sh + SKILL.md). Bash and git.
No runtime, no build step, no package manager.

It is invisible: GitHub doesn't render notes. PRs don't show them.
CI doesn't see them. This is the feature. Twenty years of git
history have a hidden layer that nobody used because the UI never
surfaced it. Agents don't need UI. They read refs.

The last point is why this matters now: coding agents start from
zero every session. They have no memory, no culture, no context
beyond what's in the repo. The code tells them WHAT exists. The
commits tell them WHEN things changed. Nothing tells them WHY,
or what the team values, or what's fragile, or what was tried
and abandoned. Mycelium fills that gap — not by adding a new
system, but by using what git already had all along.
